^z3[ADDITIONAL WAYS OF GIVING ATTENTION]^en86k In addition, attention should be given to the elements in the following ways:	(1) as to word meaning, (2) by groups, (3) by particles, (4) by characteristic, etc., (5) as to how originated, (6) as to variety and unity, (7) as to resolution (separability) and non-resolution (inseparability), (8) as to the similar and the dissimilar, (9) as to distinction between internal and external, (10) as to inclusion, (11) as to condition,	(12) as to lack of conscious reaction, (13) ^z3[as to analysis of conditions].
^n347^en87k^i[1.] Herein, one who gives his attention to them ^i[as to word meaning] should do so separately and generally thus: {separately} it is earth (^i[pathavī]) because it is spread out (^i[patthaṭa]); 
it flows (^i[appoti]) or it glides (^i[āpiyati]) or it satisfies (^i[appāyati]), thus it is water (^i[āpo]); 
it heats (^i[tejati]), thus it is fire (^i[tejo]); 
it blows (^i[vāyati]), thus it is air (^i[vāyo]). 
But without differentiation they are elements (^i[dhātu]) because of bearing (^i[dhāraṇa]) their own characteristics, because of grasping (^i[ādāna]) suffering, and because of sorting out (^i[ādhāna]) suffering (see XV.19).^f29 
This is how they should be given attention as to word meaning. ^pdf358 
^n348^en88k^i[2. By groups]: there is the earth element described under the twenty aspects (modes) beginning with head hairs, body hairs, and also the water element described under the twelve (modes) aspects beginning with bile, phlegm, etc. 
