^n716^en73t 7. Having attributed the three characteristics to that arising from nutriment, etc., he again attributes the three characteristics to natural materiality. 
^z6[Natural materiality] is a name for external materiality that is not bound up with faculties and arises along with the eon of world expansion, for example, iron, copper, tin, lead, gold, silver, pearl, gem, beryl, conch shell, marble, coral, ruby, opal, soil, stone, rock, grass, tree, creeper, and so on (see Vibh 83). 
That becomes evident to him by means of an asoka-tree shoot.
^en74t For that to begin with is pale pink; then in two or three days it becomes dense red, again in two or three days it becomes dull red, next {brown,} the colour of a tender {mango} shoot; next, the colour of a growing shoot; next, the colour of pale leaves;
next, the colour of dark green leaves. 
After it has become the colour of dark green leaves, as it follows out the successive stages of such material continuity, it eventually becomes withered foliage, and at the end of the year it breaks loose from its stem and falls off.
^en75t Discerning that, he attributes the three characteristics to it 
thus: The materiality occurring when it is pale pink ceases there without reaching the time when it is dense red; 
the materiality occurring when it is dense red … dull red; 
the materiality occurring when it is dull red … the colour of a tender {mango} shoot; 
the materiality occurring when it is the colour of a tender {mango} shoot … the colour of a growing shoot; 
the materiality occurring when it is the colour of a growing shoot … the colour of pale green leaves; 
the materiality occurring ^pdf651 when it is the colour of pale green leaves … the colour of dark green leaves; 
the materiality occurring when it is the colour of dark green leaves … the time when it is withered foliage; 
the materiality occurring when it is withered foliage ceases there without ^pts626 reaching the time when it breaks loose from its stem and falls off: 
